# Context7 — version-wise backend context only

This codebase uses **Context7 MCP** for up-to-date, version-specific documentation. Scope is **backend only** (no frontend libs).

## When to use Context7

- Library APIs, setup, or configuration for: Fastify, Drizzle, BullMQ, Postgres, Node.js
- Code examples for external packages in the backend stack
- Framework-specific patterns (routes, auth, plugins, schema, queries, queues, workers)

## Version-wise prompts

Mention versions in prompts so Context7 returns docs for the versions we use:

- **Fastify 5** — routes, auth, plugins
- **Drizzle 0.45** — postgres schema, queries, indexes
- **BullMQ 5** — redis queues, jobs, workers
- **Postgres** — pooling, connections, SQL
- **Node.js** — runtime, modules, async

Example prompts:

```
How do I add rate limiting in Fastify 5? use context7
Drizzle 0.45 migration for adding a column. use context7
BullMQ 5 job retry configuration. use context7
```

## Library IDs (skip resolution)

Use these directly when you know the library:

- `/fastify/fastify` — routes, auth, plugins
- `/drizzle-team/drizzle-orm` — postgres schema, queries, indexes
- `/optimalbits/bullmq` — redis queues, jobs
- `/postgres/postgres` — pooling, connections, SQL
- `/nodejs/node` — runtime, modules, async

Example: `use context7 with /fastify/fastify for auth plugin setup`

## Do not use Context7 for

- Frontend libs (Vite, React, Tailwind, shadcn) — not in this repo
- General coding questions unrelated to external packages
- Internal domain logic (handlers, services, repos) — use CLAUDE.md and project rules
